         <abstract xml:lang="eng">
            <p>IMS Health Holdings, a health care data and consulting firm, is a firm seeking for growth in the health care industry. The firm is considering buying a smaller company, The Advisory Board Company, or merging with Quintiles, both large companies. It is considering buying a smaller healthcare consulting firm, the Advisory Board Company (ABCO). IMS could, instead of acquiring ABCO, become acquired by Quintiles, a health care company about the same size as IMS. IMS was unsure about which action would best serve its shareholders. It could grow faster and larger through a merger with Quintiles. Would the synergies and potential economies of scale of such a merger be worthwhile? Or could it acquire a company like ABCO, which appeared to be undervalued? Would this move prove more valuable to shareholders? The rugged terrain of the healthcare industry was becoming more difficult to navigate because of the uncertain effects of the Affordable Care Act, which made healthcare available to more people, but also complicated companies’ and healthcare providers businesses.</p>
         </abstract>
